<h2 id="now-mix-and-match-these-chord-shapes">Now, mix and match these chord shapes!</h2>

<p>Think of each of these chord shapes as a building block - which can be freely used &amp; combined in any order. Keep this in mind when playing these shapes. Try out a few of them together, in a pattern, and repeat. Experiment with different strumming patterns. Play around with which strings youâ€™re accenting. Mix it up! Especially when youâ€™re warming up, this sort of free play can be very helpful to get the blood flowing and try something new.</p>

<h2 id="why-do-some-of-these-chords-sound-weird">Why do some of these chords sound weird?</h2>

<p>Youâ€™ll notice that some of these chords sound â€œbetterâ€ than others. Specifically, the E-major shape sounds the best - while the G#m sounds dissonant (and clashing to the ear). The A and the B have a major sound, but donâ€™t ring as cleanly as â€œnormalâ€ A and B chords. This is all okay! The reason is that, those open strings (the 1st, 2nd, and 6th strings) are notes that arenâ€™t used in many of these chords - which makes them sound a bit â€œoffâ€ and less defined. But, I think this is fine - music isnâ€™t always about coloring inside the lines. And while some of these chords sound cleaner than others, theyâ€™re all using notes from the key of E - so there is a nice consistency that can be heard no matter how you put them together.</p>

